<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ON THE ATTACK: A spirit of meanness is on the rise in American politics, 
according to a bevy of political heavyweights gathered this week at the Ronald 
Reagan Presidential Library near Simi Valley (B4). . . . But dirty campaigning 
has been around for decades, says Simi Valley political consultant Steve Frank 
-- at least since 1888, when President Grover Cleveland was accused of 
fathering a child out of wedlock. "Technology today is better than it's ever 
been so you can find out more," Frank said. But meanness "is nothing new. It's 
always been there." 
</P>
<P>
 JOURNEY'S END: It's been where no spacecraft has gone before -- around the 
planet Venus about 15,000 times. . . . Now, the $900-million Magellan 
spacecraft -- which experienced myriad technical problems -- is at the end of 
its deep-space voyage (B10). . . . Despite the probe's many technical problems, 
Cal Lutheran University professor Tom Janssens said it collected enough data to 
keep scientists busy for years. "It's certainly been spectacular," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 MEDFLY EXPERTS: The Cooperative Medfly Project has helped formulate Ventura 
County's plan of attack on the dreaded Medfly -- including aerial malathion 
spraying beginning tonight (B1, B6). . . . Based in Bell, the group has helped 
manage efforts to eradicate the Medfly across the state. . . . The weapons in 
their arsenal are becoming increasingly sophisticated, among them computers and 
hand-spraying from solar-powered backpacks. 
</P>
<P>
 NO FEAR: Math phobia is not a problem for three Moorpark High School students 
who excelled in the national Future Business Leaders of America competition. . 
. . Andrew Philip, Sishant Narayan and Quan Nguyen ranked among the nation's 
top high school business students, with Andrew winning top honors in business 
calculations. . . . Among the challenges: answering as many as 100 math 
questions in an hour. Moorpark regularly competes in the contest, but had one 
of its best showings this year. "It's been real exciting," said adviser Joyce 
Keefer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
